<?php $__env->startSection('content'); ?><p>I'm A Celebrity bosses have reportedly forked out millions to make the 19th-century castle where this year's series is being held in North Wales.</p>

<p>And aerial snaps revealed on Friday have shown the extent of the renovations on Gwrych Castle, in Abergele, to ensure the celebrity contestants will be comfortable during their stint.</p>

<p>A studio where hosts Ant McPartlin and Declan Donnelly has been erected, as well as an uncovered area where contestants will be allowed to light a camp fire.</p>

<p>Renovations: I'm A Celebrity bosses have added a permanent roof, a water pump and a separate studio site to Gwrych Castle it was revealed in aerial snaps shared on Friday, after 'forking out millions to make derelict site safe'</p>

<p>While there is also a section of the location where they will sleep has been covered with strong plastic to keep the winds and rain at bay.</p>

<p>Permanent roofs have also been placed across the castle to protect the contestants during bad weather, which have been put up as part of the show's agreement with the National Heritage site  to restore the castle.</p>

<p>But that's not all, as the castle is not fitted with running water so new facilities have been placed on one side of the building so that water can be pumped into the building for celebrities to use. </p>

<p> In the works: Aerial photos showed that construction is very much still underway as a crane was in operation</p>

<p>Changes: A studio where hosts Ant McPartlin and Declan Donnelly has been erected, as well as an uncovered area where contestants will be allowed to light a camp fire</p>

<p>Protection: While there is also a section of the location where they will sleep has been covered with strong plastic to keep the winds and rain at bay</p>

<p>Spacious: The castle appears to have plenty of space for contestants to walk around in during their stint</p>

<p>Helpful: Permanent roofs have also been placed across the castle to protect the contestants during bad weather, which have been put up as part of the show's agreement with the National Heritage site to restore the castle</p>

<p>The renovations have apparently been a costly affair to transform the castle into a TV set, as workers installed electrics and pipes to provide the location with running water.</p>

<p>After the coronavirus pandemic dashed hopes of the Australian jungle being this series' setting, bosses hired the castle for £1 million for six weeks.</p>

<p>According to a report from The Sun on Thursday, the star-studded line-up of campmates will be housed under a waterproof roof in a show first to protect them from the bitter UK climate.</p>

<p>A show source said: 'This isn't a holiday camp for the stars, but without a roof, everyone would have been utterly miserable for three weeks, which would not make great telly.'</p>

<p>Other areas: Another part of the castle has been left roofless, it is unclear if this section will be used for trials</p>

<p>Facilities: But that's not all, as the castle is not fitted with running water so new facilities have been placed on one side of the building so that water can be pumped into the building for celebrities to use</p>

<p>Picturesque: The castle is surrounded by luscious woodland so the contestants will remain away from society</p>

<p>Undergoing transformation: Renovations has apparently been a costly affair to transform the castle into a TV set, as workers installed electrics and pipes to provide the location with running water</p>

<p>Pricey! After the coronavirus pandemic dashed hopes of the Australian jungle being this series' setting, bosses hired the castle for £1 million for six weeks</p>

<p>The source added: 'It will still be hard work but slightly warmer than if it snows where they are sleeping. ITV want viewers to largely recognise the show.' </p>

<p>MailOnline have contacted I'm A Celebrity for comment at the time. </p>

<p>Last month Kevin Lygo, the Director of Television at ITV, has revealed that all stars for this year's I'm A Celebrity... Get Me Out Of Here! have been confirmed. </p>

<p>And while rumours circulate that Selling Sunset's Christine Quinn, presenter Vernon Kay, and Coronation Street's Beverley Callard have signed up, Lygo assures all of the as-yet-unnamed stars have been confirmed – despite the change of location.</p>

<p>Exciting: Kevin Lygo, the Director of Television at ITV, revealed that all stars for this year's I'm A Celebrity... Get Me Out Of Here! have been confirmed (hosts Ant and Dec pictured)</p>

<p>Changes: This year's I'm A Celebrity Get Me Out Of Here will be filmed in North Wales, after being forced to relocate due to the COVID-19 pandemic</p>

<p>He told The Sun: 'I certainly didn't want a year without I’m A Celebrity. We could just about survive without it, but my God it's a premier, wonderful thing that has done so well over a long period.'</p>

<p>Lygo continued: 'Australia was always going to be a challenge so we found this extraordinary place in go here in North Wales that's a sort of beautiful, Disney drawn castle crumbling. We just thought it looks like perfect vacation.'</p>

<p>With the new location, he added that 'it'll be fascinating to see what audiences do' and it will be a 'great challenge' for producers to devise new games and tasks. </p>

<p>Reports: It came as rumours swirl that Selling Sunset's Christine Quinn (left) and presenter Vernon Kay (right) could be set to enter the cast this autumn </p>

